7366713460354239790.voice_to_text: Do you have to feed your cats a wet food only diet for them to live a long, happy and healthy life? I normally don't make reaction videos like this, but I just felt. I felt like it. I felt like it today and I post on TikTok, so here I am. No disrespect to this vet at all, I just wanna share a couple thoughts that I have. Um, number one, this video was made in reaction to the video of a very sweet person talking about how her cat passed away and her vet told her that wet food would have helped prevent it. So one thing is to keep in mind that the idea that wet food could have helped prevent this passing was from a vet. It wasn't from like a random person. Secondly, I think it's disappointing that there's this idea that people who talk about nutrition on social media whatever, including vets who talk about it, are trying to guilt trip others or make them feel bad for feeding kibble. I don't think that's the intention of most people. I know a lot of wonderful creators that are just trying to share information to help people and help pets. Not everyone is trying to guilt trip someone. Um, in addition, it's really important to note that no one, or at least most people, don't think nutrition is a one way ticket to perfect health. Nutrition is one factor in health, just like a healthy Human can, like, eat a perfect diet and still get sick. But nutrition is within the owner's control. It is our responsibility to feed our pets. We can't control genetics, but we can control what our cats consume. So I don't think nutrition's role in health should be negated. And again, the most important thing that you can do, or the best thing that you can do is get information from a ton of different sources. There are plenty of vets on this app talking about the basics of cat nutrition, like the fundamental biology that cats are needing high moisture, high protein diets. So you can talk to different vets while differing opinions. You can talk to people who study nutrition. You can read books, try to get a wealth of information, come to your own conclusions, because there's really not one source of truth. And I know it's confusing and it sucks, but just try to absorb as much information as you can. And whether your opinions ultimately go with this person or air more on the fresh feeding, wet food, you know, it's your pet and you're making choices for them.

7367585272470539562.voice_to_text: improved access to veterinary care saved my cat's life let's talk about it today is May 10th which means that it's Access to Veterinary Care Awareness Day and so sharing my own story I hope that it allows my veterinary professional friends who really think about how we can play a role in bridging the gap between owners and access to veterinary care I have a community acquired cat where I found him in an abandoned apartment he wasn't chipped, he wasn't neutered, so I kept him, but then he started having horrible vomiting and diarrhea and as someone who had just barely scraped enough to pay for him to have food and water and everything that he needed in my apartment I didn't have the several hundred dollars to take him to the vet to work up what was going on with him so I actually saved up to take him to the Humane Society, and pay for their surrendering fee, because I wanted him to get the care that he needed, The Humane Society actually told me that they couldn't take him, even though I was willing to pay the surrendering fee so I had to take him to the municipal shelter in the area and I knew the statistics the cats that went into that and came out of it alive. I cried, I took him to the shelter and I walked up to the front door and I was like I'm here to surrender my cat that I clearly loved, and was crying about, and there was a rescue there who was doing diversion on purpose, for those who don't know what that means, they were talking to people who were looking to surrender their pets they were asking "why"  is it a health issue so that we can help out with and I explained to them like it's because I don't know if he's sick I can't afford it if it is something serious and so they're like, well how about we pay for you to go to the nearby vet clinic it's a walk in clinic, you have to wait all day and we'll pay for him to be neutered [at another date] and if you think that you can keep him otherwise like let's let's keep him out of the shelter it was wild; so I went from the shelter where I had been emotionally preparing to surrender my cat to this veterinary clinic where they saw him, they did a full work up on this rescue's dime, and he was otherwise healthy, was probably just dietary discretion because we had just found him, who knows what he had been eating for a week in that apartment and because of them I got to keep him and I still have him. people wanna talk about access to veterinary care like it's this horrific situation, of a poor person getting an animal that they can't take care of, but sometimes in situations like me, where I was able to take care of him otherwise and it was just that upfront cost that I didn't have the funds for, cause I didn't plan on having a cat ultimately then thanks to Banfield (which again I'm not sponsored by them) I was able to get him on a wellness plan and he has received top notch veterinary care ever since I found him and if it wasn't for that rescue intervening at the shelter you would have probably been euthanized, this list is from VetBilling, and it's kind of a good, comprehensive starting point, for what veterinary professionals can do to learn more and take action including learning about the importance of access to veterinary care adopting a spectrum of care approach to treatment rather than asuming gold standard is best or achieveable by everyone, you can offer a variety of payment plans types include sliding scale options like a EmanciPet does; VetBilling, VetBilling  other companies exist like that, you can embrace cultural sensitivity and DEI initiatives because it actually does improve profitablity, you can provide telemedicine services which have all of my friends that have companies, and veterinary clinics do that as well, and you can create an in-house angel fund or affiliate with third party charitable fund too I'm so grateful for the rescue that actually was committed to increasing access to care by helping me get my cat the care he needs, because if it wasn't for them I probably wouldn't have him, and he probably wouldn't be here ❤️

7367087875730476330.video_description: The greatest cat physicist of all time has published multiple highly-respected works to scientific journals, making lasting contributions to the field. 🐈 He was a member of the physics department at Michigan State University, along with his human roommate, mathematician and physicist Jack Hetherington. 🐈‍⬛ When he was first published, FDC Willard was an undercover cat, and it wasn’t until later that the truth was revealed. 🐱 📸 Jack Hetherington  *Some footage in this video is representative of Chester and not actual depictions of him.  #catswithjobs #introducingcats #cat #physicscat #physics #siamesecat #famouscat
7367087875730476330.voice_to_text: This is the first cat to ever publish a physics paper, and he's regarded as the greatest feline physicist of all time. His name is Chester, and he lived with a human roommate named Jack Hetherington, who was also a physicist at Michigan State University. In 1975, Jack wrote a paper about his research results, and he wanted to publish it to a scientific journal. When he had a colleague review his work, they pointed out that he had used the pronoun we instead of I and suggested that the journal would reject it as a single author submission because it was written on a typewriter. The entire paper would have had to have been retyped to fix this, so Jack decided it would just be easier to bring on a second author instead, and naturally his cat Chester was his first choice. To make it less obvious to the review board that his second author was a cat, he gave Chester the pen name FDC Willard, short for Fearless Domesticus Chester Willard, which is the scientific name for a house cat, plus Chester, plus the name of Chester's dad. The paper was accepted, and after it was published, Jack sent some signed copies to some friends, including FDC Willard's paw print. At this point, FDC Willard's cover was blown, but the physics community only embraced their new cat colleague. He went on to publish another paper as the only author, and he's highly respected for his lasting contributions to The field all of his work can be found on Google Scholar.

7366287937601817888.video_description: Should you only feed your cat wet food? Not if you don’t want to. No food for our pets is a guarentee of health and no food is a guarantee of illness and anyone implying this is the case does not have a good enough graps of nutrition to be giving advice. A mix of wet and dry is a good option for cats. It does promote hydration but it is also useful to get them used to different food textures, so if you need to change their diet you can do so reasonably easily. Cats are not big drinkers, this is true but it doesn’t follow, and there is no evidence, that feeding only dry food leaves them ‘chronically dehydrated’ When it comes to urinary and kidney health, the quality and mineral content of the diet, wet or dry, is what makes the most difference.  But even then, healthy cats should be able to manage just fine if your budget only extends to the more cost effective options (and look for the lower cost diets produced by science based brands, their knowledge & quality extends to all their lines!) I despise scaremongering and accusatory videos on nutrition. They do nothing but worry pet owners and, very often, they also undermine the trust and relationship people have with their vet. If you ever see anything online that makes you question how you care for your pet, please reach out to the staff at your local clinic. They will be more than happy to help you and guide you on what will work best for you and your animals. #cathealth #catfood #felinenutrition #askyourvet #catthevet And thanks as always to @FIGS for my lovely #gifted scrub top!
7366287937601817888.voice_to_text: Do you have to feed your cat a wet food only diet for them to live a long happy and healthy life? No. If you feed your cat a 100% wet food diet will that stop them getting urinary problems? No. Will it stop them getting urinary blockages? No. Will it prevent them from getting kidney failure? No. If you want to feed your cat a 100% wet food diet, as a recently viral video on here has been advocating, then that is absolutely fine but it is not a guarantee of health or welfare for your cat. Ut's true that our cats aren't naturally big drinkers but as long as we provide water freely available and in a way that they want so moving, wide, flat filled to the brim, I've discussed it in other videos, that is absolutely fine, they will drink. If you feed your cat dry food that does not automatically mean that they're going to get urinary problems or kidney failure or obesity or diabetes. No food is a one way ticket to health and no food is a one way ticket to illness. And any person claiming that that is the case, does not know enough about nutrition to be giving advice.

7361954689795018027.voice_to_text: so everybody thinks my cat is 💀  and I got way too many comments to not talk about it I made a video saying that I woke up to nanaki sitting in the bathtub staring at the wall I did a bit of digging into it because when everyone says that your cat is 💀  you you kinda wanna look into it and yes cat staring at a wall can be a symptom of a few bad things but I promise you that's not the case with him there's a handful of different reasons that a cat could be staring at a wall not all of them are morbid one of the big ones is feline cognitive dysfunction which typically happens in cats that are more than 10 years old this guy is a year and a half old It’s basically kitty alzheimer's your brain changes and your behavior starts to change with it they'll they'll wander around they'll stare at walls they scream they yell another one is feeling hyperesthesia which is typically hypersensitivity in the skin but it can come along with some other symptoms one of them being staring at a wall and the one that you really don't wanna see is head pressing that's where they physically press their head against the wall and stand there they don't just stare at it that is a bad sign no matter what that usually indicates a brain tumor or some disease go to the vet on a lighter note cats can also stare at walls because they can see a wider range than we do so they might see a bug or something that we don't see or a small speck of light their hearing is also way better so they might hear a mouse behind the wall that I couldn't hear which is probably likely what he was doing and the third and most light hearted reason for why cats stare at walls is because sometimes they're just silly little guys he he's just he's just goofy he's fine I promise

7346760273321069856.voice_to_text: Will your cat forget you? The answer might shock you. Cat memories are divided into short term and long term. Their short term memory last about 16 hours. They might not remember specific events, but they do remember essential survival info, like which cabinet hides the treats or which bowl has food. They've got it all mapped out. And when it comes to long term memories, cats can remember skills for opening doors, windows, and even cabinets, keeping these memories for 10 years or more. But here's come the interesting part. When it comes to people, cats are picky about what they remember. Thanks to their self domestication, they only hold on to memories of people and things that are useful to them. If you feed them, give them a home, and care for them with love, they associate you with all the good in their world, creating a bond that lasts a lifetime. There was a cat raised by an elderly person from kittenhood when the owner fell ill and had to give the cat away. Even after two years apart, the cat still recognized their voice. The cat may think you just stepped out for a while, but you never truly leave their memory. So do you think your furry friend remembers all the good times you've shared? They do, more than you might realize. Share this with a cat lover and follow us for more heartwarming cat tales!
